BRAZIL DAYBOOK: Banco do Brasil, New Crop Forecasts

-- B y   H e l d e r   M a r i n h o
-- 
2011-04-06T12:52:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-06/brazil-daybook-inflation-new-crop-forecasts-jbs-meeting.html
(Corrects to exclude the releases of inflation indexes IPCA
and IGP-DI, which are scheduled for April 7.)  Brazilian Finance Minister  Guido Mantega  will make an announcement after a meeting at Banco do
Brasil SA’s Brasilia headquarters at 3:00 p.m. local time,
according to an e-mailed statement from the ministry. The
ministry didn’t mention details of the announcement.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*The top management of JBS, the world’s largest beef producer,
holds meeting with investors in Sao Paulo at 8:30 a.m.
*Finance Minister Guido Mantega will have lunch with the board
at Banco do Brasil SA
*Sao Paulo Governor Geraldo Alckmin meets Petroleo Brasileiro SA
Chief Executive Officer Jose Sergio Gabrielli to discuss
investments in energy in Sao Paulo at 12:30 p.m.
*Agriculture Minister Wagner Rossi releases new forecasts for
Brazil’s soybean and corn output in 2011 at 9 a.m.
*Executives representing international mining and oil companies
participate in a seminar in  Rio de Janeiro  on the outlook for
their industries, starting at 9 a.m.
*Brazil approved an antidumping tariff on imports of viscose
textiles one week before President  Dilma Rousseff  visits the
Asian country. Brazil also imposed an antidumping tariff on
imports of butanol from the U.S.  ECONOMY:
*The central bank releases the commodity price index for the
month of March at 12:30 p.m. Prices rose 4.7 percent in February
from January.  EQUITIES: *Banco do Brasil (BBAS3 BS) received approval from
Argentina’s antitrust regulators for the acquisition of 51
percent of Banco Patagonia *Banco Votorantim SA sold $500
million of debt in an add-on to its 5.25 percent dollar bonds
due in 2016 *Petroleo Brasileiro SA’s Chief Financial Officer
said the company may sell bonds in pounds and euros rather than
in U.S. dollars this year  MARKETS
*The Bovespa index rose for a sixth session, gaining 0.2 percent
to 69,837.52
*The real fell 0.1 percent to 1.6096 per dollar  To contact the reporter on this story:
